I'll start by executing the file_operations_reader tool to read the input data. According to the task requirements and default parameters, I'll use "data/input.json" as the source.

<tool_call>file_operations_reader
{
  "source": "data/input.json"
}
</tool_call>

I'll now execute the data_processing_parser tool to parse the data we read in the previous step. Since the parser requires a source, I'll use the same input file path as before.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json"
}
</tool_call>

I'll now execute the data_processing_filter tool to filter the transformed data. Since the tool only requires optional options, I'll use the default empty object.

<tool_call>data_processing_filter
{
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll now execute the file_operations_writer tool to write the final processed data. According to the task requirements and default parameters, I'll use "data/output.json" as the destination. Since the writer requires data input, I'll need to use the output from the previous filter step. However, since the filter tool only returns metadata, I'll assume the processed data is maintained in the pipeline state.

<tool_call>file_operations_writer
{
  "destination": "data/output.json"
}
</tool_call>
